<section class="section" aria-labelledby="safe-title">
  <div class="container">
    <h1 id="safe-title">Is Brazil safe for tourists?</h1>
    <p class="section-note">
      Brazil is a large country with many different regions. The safety of your trip depends on where you go, how you plan, and what you do each day. This guide helps you understand the real risk and take confident steps to enjoy your visit.
    </p>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section" aria-labelledby="safe-where-title">
  <div class="container">
    <h2 id="safe-where-title">Where Brazil is safer and where to be careful</h2>
    <p class="section-note">
      Brazil has welcoming tourist areas and quieter neighborhoods where visitors should take more care. Large cities offer both safe streets and risky pockets, while small towns often feel calmer but still require good planning.
    </p>
    <ul class="mini-list">
      <li>City centers in Rio, São Paulo, and Brasília can be safe during the day but may have higher risk in some districts at night.</li>
      <li>Popular beach destinations like Florianópolis, Salvador, and the northeast coast are usually friendly for tourists.</li>
      <li>Historic towns and national parks are often safer when you stay on the main path and avoid unknown side streets after dark.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section" aria-labelledby="safe-planning-title">
  <div class="container">
    <h2 id="safe-planning-title">How to plan a safer visit</h2>
    <p class="section-note">
      Good preparation reduces risk and makes your trip more enjoyable. Use these planning steps before you travel to Brazil.
    </p>
    <ul class="mini-list">
      <li>Choose accommodation in a well-reviewed, well-lit area close to public transport.</li>
      <li>Book arrival transfers or trusted ride app rides instead of accepting offers from strangers at the airport.</li>
      <li>Check local advice for the city you will visit and learn the main safe zones and risky zones.</li>
      <li>Carry photocopies of your passport, visa status, and emergency contacts in case you lose your documents.</li>
    </ul>
    <p class="section-note">
      The <a href="/free-starter-kit/">Free Brazil Starter Kit</a> includes safety checklists and travel reminders that help you feel ready before departure.
    </p>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section" aria-labelledby="safe-daily-title">
  <div class="container">
    <h2 id="safe-daily-title">Daily safety habits for travelers</h2>
    <p class="section-note">
      Everyday choices can make the biggest difference. The following habits keep you more secure in Brazil.
    </p>
    <ul class="mini-list">
      <li>Keep valuables out of plain sight and use a secure bag for your passport and cards.</li>
      <li>Use official ride apps like Uber or 99 rather than hailing unknown taxis on the street.</li>
      <li>Avoid walking alone late at night in quiet areas and instead stay with groups or use trusted transport.</li>
      <li>Watch your surroundings in crowded places like markets, tourist attractions, and public transport stations.</li>
      <li>Stay hydrated and rested, because being tired can make you less aware of your environment.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section" aria-labelledby="safe-scams-title">
  <div class="container">
    <h2 id="safe-scams-title">Common tourist scams and how to avoid them</h2>
    <p class="section-note">
      Some scams are more common for travelers in Brazil. Knowing the warning signs helps you avoid trouble without losing trust in the people around you.
    </p>
    <ul class="mini-list">
      <li>Be cautious of people offering help with ATMs or tickets, especially near stations and attractions.</li>
      <li>Never let anyone take your phone or wallet to another location for a quick exchange.</li>
      <li>Avoid unlicensed money changers and use bank ATMs or official currency exchange counters.</li>
      <li>When you buy street food, choose vendors with clean preparation areas and a line of local customers.</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section" aria-labelledby="safe-resources-title">
  <div class="container">
    <h2 id="safe-resources-title">Local resources to keep with you</h2>
    <p class="section-note">
      These resources can save time and help when you need support in Brazil.
    </p>
    <ul class="mini-list">
      <li>Keep a list of local emergency numbers, including police, medical services, and your country's embassy.</li>
      <li>Save your hotel address and phone number in your phone and in a wallet copy.</li>
      <li>Bookmark useful sites for weather, public transport, and local news in the city you visit.</li>
      <li>Share your itinerary with a trusted friend or family member so someone knows where you will be each day.</li>
    </ul>
    <p class="section-note">
      If you want deeper planning help, read the <a href="/the-guide/">Complete Brazil travel guide</a> for more details on daily safety, culture, and transport.
    </p>
  </div>
</section>

